Description: CmeABC is a multidrug efflux pump in Campylobacter jejuni. Its overexpression led to enhanced resistance to ciprofloxacin, norfloxacin, cefotaxime, fusidic acid, and erythromycin. CmeA acts as the periplasmic fusion protein, CmeB is the inner membrane transporter, and CmeC is an outer membrane protein.

Name: adeA
Description: AdeA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex AdeABC.

Name: adeB
Description: AdeB is the multidrug transporter of the adeABC efflux system.

Name: Enterococcus faecium adeC
Description: AdeC is the outer membrane factor of the AdeABC multidrug efflux complex. It can be replaced by other outer membrane channels, and is not essential for antibiotic resistance.

Name: adeF
Description: AdeF is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex AdeFGH.

Name: adeG
Description: AdeG is the inner membrane transporter of the AdeFGH multidrug efflux complex.

Name: adeH
Description: AdeH is the outer membrane channel protein of the AdeFGH multidrug efflux complex.

Name: adeI
Description: AdeI is the membrane fusion protein of the AdeIJK multidrug efflux complex.

Name: adeJ
Description: AdeJ is a RND efflux protein that acts as the inner membrane transporter of the AdeIJK efflux complex. It has 57% identity with E. coli AcrB.

Name: adeK
Description: AdeK is the outer membrane factor protein in the adeIJK multidrug efflux complex.

Name: cmeA
Description: CmeA is the membrane fusion protein of the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.

Name: cmeB
Description: CmeB is the inner membrane transporter the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.

Name: cmeC
Description: CmeC is the outer membrane channel protein of the CmeABC multidrug efflux complex.

Name: MdsABC
Description: MdsABC, or GesABC, is a RND-type efflux complex found in Salmonella. In addition to its metal-efflux system, GesABC is also capable of exporting beta-lactams, chloramphenicol, and thiamphenicol. GesB is the inner membrane transporter and is similar to MexF; GesA is the membrane-fusion protein, and GesC is the outer membrane factor.

Name: MdtABC-TolC
Description: MdtABC-TolC is a multidrug efflux system in Gram-negative bacteria, including E. coli and Salmonella. MdtA is a membrane fusion protein; TolC is the outer membrane channel; MdtBC form a drug transporter. In the absence of MdtB, the MdtAC-TolC has narrower drug specificity, leading to the loss of novobiocin resistance, for example.

Name: MdtEF-TolC
Description: MdtEF-TolC is a multidrug efflux complex in Gram-negative bacteria, including E. coli. MdtE is the membrane fusion protein, MdtF is the inner membrane transporter, while TolC is the outer membrane channel.

Name: mdsA
Description: MdsA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC.

Name: mdsB
Description: MdsB is the inner membrane transporter of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC.

Name: mdsC
Description: MdsC is the outer membrane channel of the multidrug and metal efflux complex MdsABC.

Name: mdtA
Description: MdtA is the membrane fusion protein of the multidrug efflux complex mdtABC.

Name: mdtB
Description: MdtB is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtC to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex.

Name: mdtC
Description: MdtC is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtB to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex. In the absence of MdtB, MdtC can form a homomultimer complex that results in a functioning efflux complex with a narrower drug specificity.

Name: mdtE
Description: MdtE is the membrane fusion protein of the MdtEF multidrug efflux complex. It shares 70% sequence similarity with AcrA.

Name: mdtF
Description: MdtF is the multidrug inner membrane transporter for the MdtEF-TolC efflux complex.

Name: MexCD-OprJ
Description: MexCD-OprJ is a multidrug efflux protein expressed in the Gram-negative Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexC is the membrane fusion protein; MexD is the inner membrane transporter; and OprJ is the outer membrane channel. MexAB-OprM is associated with resistance to fluoroquinolones, chloramphenicol, and macrolides.

Name: MexEF-OprN
Description: MexEF-OprN is a multidrug efflux protein expressed in the Gram-negative Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexE is the membrane fusion protein; MexF is the inner membrane transporter; and OprN is the outer membrane channel. MexEF-OprN is associated with resistance to fluoroquinolones, chloramphenicol, and trimethoprim.

Name: MexGHI-OpmD
Description: MexGHI-OpmD is an efflux complex expressed in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexG is a membrane protein required for drug export; MexH is the membrane fusion protein; MexI is the inner membrane transporter; and MexJ is the outer membrane channel protein. MexGHI-OpmD confers resistance to vanadium, norfloxacin, and acriflavin.

Name: mexC
Description: MexC is the membrane fusion protein of the MexCD-OprJ multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexD
Description: MexD is the multidrug inner membrane transporter of the MexCD-OprJ complex.

Name: oprJ
Description: OprJ is the outer membrane channel component of the MexCD-OprJ multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexE
Description: MexE is the membrane fusion protein of the MexEF-OprN multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexF
Description: MexF is the multidrug inner membrane transporter of the MexEF-OprN complex.

Name: oprN
Description: OprN is the outer membrane channel component of the MexEF-OprN multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexG
Description: MexG is a membrane protein required for MexGHI-OpmD efflux activity.

Name: mexH
Description: MexH is the membrane fusion protein of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.

Name: mexI
Description: MexI is the inner membrane transporter of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.

Name: opmD
Description: OpmD is the outer membrane channel protein of the efflux complex MexGHI-OpmD.

Name: mtrC
Description: MtrC is the membrane fusion protein of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mtrD
Description: MtrD is the inner membrane multidrug transporter of the MtrCDE efflux complex.

Name: mtrE
Description: MtrE is an outer membrane exporter protein that is part of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexS
Description: MexS is a suppressor of MexT, which is an activator of the multidrug pump MexEF-OprN. Mutations in MexS lead to multidrug resistance.

Name: mexT
Description: MexT is a LysR-type transcriptional activator that positively regulates the expression of MexEF-OprN and OprD.

Name: mgrA
Description: MgrA, also known as NorR, is a regulator for norA, norB, and tet38. It is a positive regulator for norA expression, but is a direct repressor for norB and an indirect repressor of tet38.

Name: mtrA
Description: MtrA is a transcriptional activator of the MtrCDE multidrug efflux pump of Neisseria gonorrhoeae.

Name: mtrR
Description: MtrR is a repressor of mtrCDE expression. Mutations in mtrR increase multidrug resistance.

Name: nalC
Description: NalC is a repressor of PA3720-PA3719, which are positive regulators of MexAB-OprM. Thus, nalC mutants confer multidrug resistance.

Name: nalD
Description: NalD is a repressor of MexAB-OprM. Mutations lead to multidrug resistance and MexAB-OprM overexpression.

Name: nfxB
Description: NfxB is a repressor of the efflux pump mexCD-oprJ and itself.

Name: phoPQ
Description: PhoPQ is a two-component regulatory system. phoP is phosphorylated by phoQ at a low [mg2+], activating the repressor. Its part of a two component regulating system that activates the PmrA/B system which has downstream effects, leading to Antimicrobial resistance in many pathogens. In Salmonella, phoP bind to macAB ABC transporter and represses it. In Escherichia coli, phoPQ regulates arnA expression. In Pseudomonas aeruginosa, phoPQ regulates OprH expression. phoPQ have other roles in other species.

Name: pmrA efflux pump
Description: PmrA is a MFS-type efflux pump expressed in Streptococcus pneumoniae that confers low-level resistance to norfloxacin, ciprofloxacin, and acriflavine.

Name: ramA
Description: RamA ("resistance antibiotic multiple") is a positive regulator of AcrAB-TolC and leads to high level multidrug resistance in Klebsiella pneumoniae, Salmonella enterica, and Enterobacter aerugenes, increasing the expression of both the mar operon as well as AcrAB. RamA also decreases OmpF expression.

Name: ramR
Description: RamR is a repressor that regulates RamA expression. Mutations lead to the upregulation of AcrAB, which is positively regulated by RamA.

Name: robA
Description: robA is a positive regulator for the acrAB efflux genes, and is structurally similar to SoxS and MarA.

Name: sdiA
Description: SdiA is a cell division regulator that is also a positive regulator of AcrAB only when it's expressed from a plasmid. When the sdiA gene is on the chromosome, it has no effect on expression of acrAB

Name: soxRS
Description: SoxRS is a two-component regulator part of the superoxide stress response. It is a positive regulator for many multidrug efflux pumps.

Name: baeR
Description: BaeR is a response regulator that promotes the expression of MdtABC and AcrD efflux complexes.

Name: baeS
Description: BaeS is a sensor kinase in the BaeSR regulatory system. While it phosphorylates BaeR to increase its activity, BaeS is not necessary for overexpressed BaeR to confer resistance.

Name: cpxA
Description: CpxA is a membrane-localized sensor kinase that is activated by envelope stress. It starts a kinase cascade that activates CpxR, which promotes efflux complex expression.

Name: cpxR
Description: CpxR is a regulator that promotes acrD expression when phosphorylated by a cascade involving CpxA, a sensor kinase.

Name: evgA
Description: EvgA, when phosphorylated, is a positive regulator for efflux protein complexes emrKY and mdtEF. While usually phosphorylated in a EvgS dependent manner, it can be phosphorylated in the absence of EvgS when overexpressed.

Name: evgS
Description: EvgS is a sensor protein that phosphorylates the regulatory protein EvgA.

Name: phoP
Description: PhoP is a direct repressor of the macAB efflux genes.

Name: phoQ
Description: PhoQ is a sensor protein that is induced by low Mg2+ concentrations. When activated, PhoQ donates a phosphate to activate PhoP.

Name: soxR
Description: SoxR is a sensory protein that upregulates soxS expression in the presence of redox-cycling drugs. This stress response leads to the expression many multidrug efflux pumps. In Pseudomonas aeruginosa, which lacks SoxS, SoxR is able to directly upregulate the expression of the MexGHI-OpmD efflux pump.

Name: soxS
Description: SoxS is a global regulator that up-regulates the expression of AcrAB efflux genes. It also reduces OmpF expression to decrease cell membrane permeability.

Name: arlR
Description: ArlR is a response regulator that binds to the norA promoter to activate expression. ArlR must first be phosphorylated by ArlS.

Name: arlS
Description: ArlS is a protein histidine kinase that phosphorylates ArlR, a promoter for norA expression.

Name: JOHN-1 beta-lactamase
Description: JOHN-1 is an Ambler class B carbapenem-hydrolysing beta-lactamase from Flavobacterium johnsoniae.

Name: CGB-1 beta-lactamase
Description: CGB-1 is an Ambler class B beta-lactamase that mediates resistance for carbapenems in Chryseobacterium gleum

Name: EBR-1 beta-lactamase
Description: EBR-1 is an Ambler class B beta-lactamase found in Empedobacter brevis and is known to mediate the hydrolysis of penicillins, cephalosporins, and carbapenems efficiently but not aztreonam.

Name: MUS-1 beta-lactamase
Description: MUS-1 is a chromosome-encoded beta-lactamase from Myroides odoratus and Myroides odoratimimus.

Name: TUS-1 beta-lactamase
Description: TUS-1 is a chromosome-encoded beta-lactamase from Myroides odoratus and Myroides odoratimimus

Name: GIM-1
Description: GIM-1 is an integron-encoded B1 beta-lactamase found in Pseudomonas aeruginosa

Name: SIM-1 beta-lactamase
Description: SIM-1 is an integron-encoded Ambler class B beta-lactamase isolated from Acinetobacter baumannii

Name: KHM-1 beta-lactamase
Description: KHM-1 is a plasmid-mediated metallo-beta-lactamase found in Citrobacter freundii

Name: DIM-1
Description: Dutch imipenemase or DIM-1 is an integron-encoded metallo-beta-lactamase from Pseudomonas stutzeri

Name: Sfh-1
Description: Sfh-I confers carbapenem resistance to Serratia fonticola

Name: GOB-1 beta-lactamase
Description: GOB-1 confers resistance to cephalosporins in Elizabethkingia meningoseptica

Name: THIN-B beta-lactamase
Description: THIN-B, isolated from Janthinobacterium lividum, hydrolyzes a broad spectrum of beta-lactams including penicillins, cephalosporins, and carbapenems.

Name: AIM-1
Description: AIM-1 is an Ambler class B beta-lactamase that hydrolyzes most beta-lactams except aztreonam and ceftazidime. It was isolated from Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

Name: SMB-1 beta-lactamase
Description: SMB-1 can hydrolyze a variety of beta-lactams, including penicillins, cephalosporins, and carbapenems. It was identified in Serratia marcescens.

Name: CAU-1 beta-lactamase
Description: CAU-1 is a B3 metallo-beta-lactamase that is encoded by the Caulobacter crescentus chromosome

Name: BJP-1
Description: BJP-1 is a subclass B3 ortholog found in Bradyrhizobium japonicum that hydrolyzes most beta-lactams except aztreonam, ticarcillin, and temocillin.

Name: 16S ribosomal RNA methyltransferase
Description: Methyltransferases that modify the 16S rRNA of the 30S subunit of bacterial ribosomes, conferring resistance to drugs that target 16S rRNA.

Name: armA
Description: ArmA is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase that targets mature or nearly mature 30S subunits. It transfers a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to N7-G1405 of the 16S rRNA, an aminoglycoside binding site.

Name: rmtA
Description: RmtA is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase found in Pseudomonas aeruginosa which methylates G1405 of the 16S rRNA. It confers high level resistance to many aminoglycosides.

Name: rmtB
Description: RmtB is a 16S rRNA methyltransferase that targets mature or nearly mature 30S subunits. It transfers a methyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine to N7-G1405 of the 16S rRNA, an aminoglycoside binding site.

Name: rmtC
Description: RmtC is a rRNA methyltransferase found in Proteus mirabilis with high level resistance to similar to aminoglycosides, with the exception of non-4,6-disubstituted deoxystreptamines (streptomycin and neomycin). It has also been isolated in Salmonella enterica ser. Virchow. It is hypothesized to methylate G1405, like related methyltransferases RmtA, RmtB, and ArmA.

Name: sgm
Description: Sgm, or sisomicin-gentamicin methyltransferase, methylates G1405 of 16S rRNA to confer resistance to various aminoglycosides.

Name: defensin resistant mprF
Description: MprF is a integral membrane protein that modifies the negatively-charged phosphatidylglycerol on the membrane surface of both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. This confers resistance to cationic peptides that disrupt the cell membrane, including defensins.

Name: fluoroquinolone resistant gyrB
Description: Point mutations in DNA gyrase subunit B (gyrB) observed in Mycobacterium tuberculosis can result in resistance to fluoroquinolones.

Name: oleD
Description: OleD is a glycotransferase found in Streptomyces antibioticus, a natural producer  of oleandomycin. OleD can glycosylate a wide range of macrolides. Unlike oleI, oleD is not found in the oleandomycin biosynthetic cluster.

Name: oleI
Description: OleI is a glycosyltransferase found in Streptomyces antibioticus, specifically the oleandomycin biosynthetic cluster. OleI glycosylates oleandomycin to confer self-resistance.

Name: oleandomycin
Description: Oleandomycin is a 14-membered macrolide produced by Streptomyces antibioticus. It is ssimilar to erythromycin, and contains a desosamine amino sugar and an oleandrose sugar. It targets the 50S ribosomal subunit to prevent protein synthesis.

Name: streptothricin resistance gene
Description: Genes conferring resistance to streptothricins.

Name: streptothricin acetyltransferase (sat)
Description: AcetylCoA dependent acetyltransferase that acetylate streptothricins such as nourseothricin at position 16 (beta position of beta-lysine).

Name: triclosan
Description: Triclosan is a common antibacterial agent added to many consumer products as a biocide.  It is an inhibitor of fatty acid biosynthesis by blocking enoyl-carrier protein reductase (FabI).

Name: fatty acid synthesis enzyme targeted by antibiotic
Description: Antibiotics can target bacteria-specific fatty acid biosynthesis enzymes.

Name: fabI
Description: FabI is an enoyl reductase enzyme that synthesizes type II fatty acids.

Name: bleomycin resistance protein (BRP)
Description: A diverse set of acidic proteins that are able to complex bleomycin and thus prevent bleomycin-induced DNA cleavage.

Name: antibiotic inactivation by sequestration
Description: Inactivation of an antibiotic by formation of a complex, preventing interaction of the antibiotic with its target.

Name: gene involved in antibiotic sequestration
Description: A gene whose product inactivates an antibiotic by formation of a complex, preventing interaction of the antibiotic with its target.

Name: methicillin resistant PBP2
Description: In methicillin sensitive S. aureus (MSSA), beta-lactams bind to native penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs) and disrupt synthesis of the cell membrane's peptidoglycan layer. In methicillin resistant S. aureus (MRSA), foreign PBP2a acquired by lateral gene transfer is able to perform peptidoglycan synthesis in the presence of beta-lactams.

Name: mecC
Description: A foreign PBP2a acquired by lateral gene transfer that able to perform peptidoglycan synthesis in the presence of beta-lactams.

Name: mdtM
Description: Multidrug resistance protein MdtM

Name: mdtL
Description: Multidrug resistance protein MdtL

Name: mdtH
Description: Multidrug resistance protein MdtH

Name: trimethoprim resistance gene
Description: Genes conferring resistance to trimethoprim

Name: trimethoprim resistant dihydrofolate reductase dfr
Description: Alternative dihydropteroate synthase dfr present on plasmids produces alternate proteins that are less sensitive to trimethoprim from inhibiting its role in folate synthesis, thus conferring trimethoprim resistance.

Name: elfamycin
Description: Elfamycins are molecules that inhibit bacterial elongation factor Tu (EF-Tu), a key protein which brings aminoacyl-tRNA (aa-tRNA) to the ribosome during protein synthesis. Elfamycins defined by their target (EF-Tu), rather than a conserved chemical backbone. Elfamycins follow two mechanisms to disrupt protein synthesis: 1. kirromycins and enacyloxin fix EF-Tu in the GTP bound conformation and lock EF-Tu onto the ribosome, and 2. pulvomycin and GE2270 cover the binding site of aa-tRNA disallowing EF-Tu from being charged with aa-tRNA. All elfamycins cause increased the affinity of EF-Tu for GTP.

Name: factumycin
Description: Factumycin is a kirromycin-like antibiotic produced by Kitasatospora setae and Streptomyces strains. Its biosynthetic cluster has been characterized which has interesting acetyl transferase domains in trans, or outside of the polyketide synthase domains. Factumycin has specific, rather than broad spectrum,  antibacterial properties, especially targeting various Acinetobacter baumanii strains.

Name: josamycin
Description: A macrolide antibiotic from Streptomyces narbonensis subsp. josamyceticus. The drug has antimicrobial activity against a wide spectrum of pathogens.

Name: chalcomycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces bikiniensis

Name: midecamycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces mycarofaciens.

Name: mycinamicin
Description: Produced by Micromonospora griseorubida.

Name: megalomycin
Description: Produced by Micromonospora megalomicia.

Name: narbomycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces narbonensis.

Name: kitasamycin
Description: Kitasamycin is a macrolide antibiotic and is produced by Streptoverticillium kitasatoense. The drug has antimicrobial activity against a wide spectrum of pathogens.

Name: carbomycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces halstedii and Streptomyces thermotolerans.

Name: rosaramicin
Description: Produced by Micromonospora rosaria.

Name: niddamycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces caelestis.

Name: celesticetin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces caelestis, which also produces the macrolide niddamycin.

Name: methymycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces venezuelae ATCC 15439.

Name: pikromycin
Description: Produced by Streptomyces venezuelae ATCC 15439.

Name: kirromycin
Description: Kirromycin, also known as mocimycin, is the representative molecule of its own class of elfamycins which is composed of more than 10 analogs. Kirromycin binds to the domain 1,2 interface of elongation factor Tu. This interaction maintains the EF-Tu*GTP conformation even after GTP is hydrolyzed to GDP. EF-Tu*GDP normally releases aa-tRNA and then exits the ribosome; however, kirromycin*EF-Tu*GDP*aa-tRNA forms a strong complex and remains bound to the ribosome, prohibits translocation of the peptide chain and translation is halted.

Name: aurodox
Description: Aurodox is an elongation factor Tu inhibiting antibiotic. It was first referred to as X-5108. It is produced by Streptomyces goldiniensis var. goldiniensis and is active primarily against gram-positive bacteria.

Name: efrotomycin
Description: Efrotomycin is produced by Streptomyces lactamodurans NRRL 3802. This kirromycin-like antibiotic is used in animal agriculture, especially in the production of swine. Generally gram negative bacteria are susceptible to efrotomycin, while gram positive bacteria are resistant.

Name: GE2270A
Description:
GE2270A is the model molecule of cyclic thiazolyl peptide elfamycins. 
GE2270A is produced by Planobispora rosea. Biosynthesis of the molecule has been shown to originate as a ribosomally synthesized peptide that undergoes significant post-translational modification. Clinical use of cyclic thiazolyl peptides is hindered by their low water solubility and bioavailability.

Name: enacyloxin IIa
Description: Enacyloxin IIa is structurally distinct but acts in a similar mechanism to kirromycin-like elfamycins. It prohibits the transfer of the amino acid at the A site to the elongating peptide chain. It is most likely that the mechanism of action is that EF-Tu*GDP is locked in the EF-Tu*GTP form, and EF-Tu*GDP*aa-tRNA is immobilized on the ribosome. It is an open question whether enacyloxin IIa actually belongs to the kirromycin-like group of elfamycins due to their high similarity.

Name: kirrothricin
Description: Kirrothricin is produced by Streptomyces cinnamoneus and is structurally related to kirromycin, aurodox, heneicomycin and shares a similar spectrum of antibacterial activity.

Name: azdimycin
Description: Azdimycin is produced by Streptomyces diastatochromogenes ATCC 31013.

Name: dihydromocimycin
Description: Dihydromocimycin is produced by Streptomyces ramocissimus CBS190.69.

Name: phenelfamycin A
Description: Phenelfamycin A was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin A has a monosaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin B. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile.

Name: phenelfamycin B
Description: Phenelfamycin B was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin B has a monosaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin A. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile.

Name: phenelfamycin C
Description: Phenelfamycin C was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin C has a disaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin D. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile.

Name: phenelfamycin D
Description: Phenelfamycin D was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin D has a disaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin C. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile.

Name: phenelfamycin E
Description: Phenelfamycin E was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin E has a trisaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin F. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile. Phenelfamycin E and F are the most potent of the phenelfamycins.

Name: phenelfamycin F
Description: Phenelfamycin F was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Phenelfamycin F has a trisaccaride moeity and is isomeric with phenelfamycin E. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile. Phenelfamycin E and F are the most potent of the phenelfamycins.

Name: unphenelfamycin
Description: Unphenelfamycin was isolated from two environmental isolates called AB999F-80 and AB1047T-33. They were both identified as Streptomyces violaceoniger strains. Both these strains were found to produce phenelfamycins A-F and unphenelfamycin. Unphenelfamycin has a monosaccaride moeity and lacks the  phenacetyl moeity present in the other phenelfamycins. All phenelfamycins were selected due to their activity against anaerobic bacteria, especially Clostridium difficile.

Name: L-681,217
Description: L-681217 is a kirromycin-like antibiotic produced by Streptomyces cattleya. Its biosynthetic gene cluster is characterized.

Name: GE37468
Description: GE37468 is a thiazolyl peptide produced by Streptomyces ATCC 55365. GE37468 is produced by post-transcription modification of a ribosomally synthesized preprotein, of which the biosynthetic gene cluster has been elucidated.

Name: amythiamicin A
Description: Amythiamicin A is a cyclic thiazolyl peptide antibiotic with a structure similar to GE2270A. Amythiamicin B, C, and D also exist, but are not discussed further here. Amythiamicin A was shown to have the highest activity in cell free protein synthesis assays.

Name: heneicomycin
Description: Heneicomycin is a kirromycin-like antibiotic, isolated from Streptomyces filipinensis. It is structurally related to kirromycin, aurodox and efrotomycin.

Name: Erm(30)
Description: Erm(30) confers a MLSb resistant phenotype. Along with erm(31), these genes are responsible for self-resistance in the pikromycin/narbomycin/methymycin/neomethymycin producer, Streptomyces venezuelae.

Name: desR
Description: B-Glycosidase involved in Streptomyces venezuelae self-resistance. This organism produces pikromycin/narbomycin/methymycin/neomethymycin which are inactivated by a glucosyltransferase inside the cell. DesR is a secreted enzyme that re-activates the antibiotic by removing the glucose once it is pumped out of the cell.

Name: verdamicin
Description: A gentamicin-group aminoglycoside isolated from Micromonospora.

Name: vertilimicin
Description: A semisynthetic genamicin-group aminoglycoside, derived from verdamicin.

Name: kasugamicin
Description: An unusual aminoglycoside because the cyclitol ring is not amino substituted; it was discovered as a fermentation product of Streptomyces kasugaensis.

Name: oleR
Description: B-Glycosidase involved in Streptomyces antibioticus self-resistance. This organism produces oleandomycin which is inactivated by glucosyltransferase (OleI or OleD) inside the cell. OleR is a secreted enzyme that re-activates the antibiotic by removing the glucose once it is pumped out of the cell.

Name: non-erm 23S ribosomal RNA methyltransferase (G748)
Description: Non-erm 23S ribosomal RNA methyltransferases modify guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering) to confer resistance to some macrolides and lincosamides,

Name: tlrB conferring tylosin resistance
Description: TlrB is a methyltransferase found in Streptomyces fradiae and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering). TlrB is found in the tylosin biosynthetic cluster and is one mechanism by which S. fradiae protects itself from self-destruction when producing this macrolide.

Name: myrA
Description: myrA is a methyltransferase found in Micromonospora griseorubida and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering) of 23S ribosomal RNA. MyrA is found in the mycinamicin biosynthetic cluster and is one mechanism by which M. griseorubida protects itself from self-destruction when producing this macrolide.

Name: RlmA(II)
Description: RlmA(II) is a methyltransferase found in Streptococcus pneumoniae and confers resistance to mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering) of 23S ribosomal RNA.

Name: chrB
Description: ChrB is a methyltransferase found in Streptomyces bikiniensis and confers resistance to chalcomycin, mycinamicin, tylosin and lincosamides. Specifically, this enzyme adds a methyl group to guanosine 748 (E. coli numbering). chrB is found in the chalcomycin biosynthetic cluster and is responsible for self-resistance in S. bikiniensis.

Name: ErmO
Description: ErmO is a methyltransferase found in the spiramycin producer Streptomyces ambofaciens. Like other Erm enzymes, it catalyzes the methylation of A2058 of the 23S ribosomal RNA. Specifically, this enzyme transfers only one methyl group. The gene is responsible for self-resistance to spiramycin.

Name: ErmS
Description: ErmS is a methyltransferase found in the tylosin producer Streptomyces fradiae. Like other Erm enzymes, it catalyzes the methylation of A2058 of the 23S ribosomal RNA. Specifically, this enzyme transfers two methyl groups. The gene is found within the tylosin biosynthetic cluster and is responsible for self-resistance

Name: ErmU
Description: ErmU is a methyltransferase found in the lincomycin producer Streptomyces lincolnensis. Like other Erm enzymes, it catalyzes the methylation of A2058 of the 23S ribosomal RNA. Specifically, this enzyme transfers only one methyl group. The gene is found in the lincomycin biosynthetic cluster and is responsible for self-resistance.

Name: ErmW
Description: ErmW is a methyltransferase found in the mycinamicin producer Micromonospora griseorubida. Like other Erm enzymes, it catalyzes the methylation of A2058 of the 23S ribosomal RNA. The gene is found within the mycinamicin biosynthetic cluster and is responsible for self-resistance.

Name: VgbA
Description: VgbA inactivates streptogramin B type antibiotics by cleaving the ester bond using an elimination mechanism.

Name: VgbB
Description: VgbB inactivates streptogramin B type antibiotics by cleaving the ester bond through an elimination mechanism.

Name: cyclic thiazolyl peptide elfamycin
Description: Cyclic thiazolyl peptide elfamycins inhibit protein synthesis by preventing the formation of the EF-Tu*GTP-aa-tRNA ternary complex, a mechanism similar to that of pulvomycin. There are non-elfamycin cyclic thiazolyl peptide antibiotics which inhibit protein synthesis by by targeting the 50S ribosomal subunit and are not discussed here further.

Name: kirromycin-like antibiotics
Description: Kirromycin-like antibiotics bind to the domain 1,2 interface of elongation factor Tu. This interaction maintains the EF-Tu*GTP conformation even after GTP is hydrolyzed to GDP. EF-Tu*GDP normally releases aa-tRNA and then exits the ribosome; however, kirromycin*EF-Tu*GDP*aa-tRNA forms a strong complex and remains bound to the ribosome, prohibits translocation of the peptide chain and translation is halted.

Name: elfamycin resistance gene
Description: Genes conferring resistance to elfamycin antibiotics.

Name: elfamycin resistant EF-Tu
Description: Sequence variants of elongation factor Tu that confer resistance to elfamycin antibiotics.

Name: facT
Description: Efflux protein facT confers resistance to factumycin. The gene has been heterologously expressed in S. coelicolor and its function was confirmed (Thaker et al. Med. Chem. Commun. 2012, 3: 1020). It is possible that this gene can efflux other kirromycin-like elfamycins, but this has not been tested.

Name: retapamulin
Description: Retapamulin is a semi-synthetic pleuromutilin antibiotic approved for the treatment of skin infections.

Name: valnemulin
Description: Two semi-synthetic pleuromutilin derivatives, tiamulin and valnemulin, have been developed as antibiotics for veterinary use.

Name: azamulin
Description: Azamulin is a semi-synthetic pleuromutilin derivative that failed Stage 1 clinical trials due to poor bioavailability.

Name: pleuromutilin
Description: Pleuromutilin is a natural product antibiotic produced by Clitopilus passeckerianus. Related antibiotics of clinical significance, such as tiamulin and retapamulin, are semi-synthetic derivatives of this compound.

Name: macrocyclic antibiotic
Description: Narrow spectrum macrocyclic antibiotics, in the general sense, is a cyclic molecule containing more than 12 atoms in the macrocyclic lactone ring.

Name: fidaxomicin
Description: A narrow spectrum antibiotic effective against Clostridium difficile infection (CDI). It is active against gram positive and gram negative bacteria by inhibiting RNA polymerase's switch region leading to cell death.

Name: SB22484
Description: SB22484 antibiotics are of the same chemical group as kirromycins. SB22484 antibiotics are produced by Streptomyces sp. NRRL 15496. There are two SB22484 isomers with the same UV absorption spectra, but differing molecular masses. These antibiotics are strongly active against Neisseria species, but also show activity against Streptococci, and Haemophilus influenzae.

Name: UK-69,753
Description: UK-69,753 is a glycosylated form of factumycin. The disaccharide moiety of UK-69,753 is virtually identical to that of efrotomycin, another member of this class of antibiotics. UK-69,753 has been shown to have strong in vitro and in vivo activity toward a swine pathogen, Treponema hyodysenteriae.

Name: phenelfamycin G
Description: Phenelfamycin G is produced by Streptomyces albospinus strain Acta 3619. Phenelfamycin G and H are isomeric and similar to phenelfamycin E and F only with the addition of a hydroxyl group at position C-30. Phenelfamycin G and H have a narrow antibacterial spectrum with potent activity against Propionibacterium acnes.

Name: phenelfamycin H
Description: Phenelfamycin H is produced by Streptomyces albospinus strain Acta 3619. Phenelfamycin G and H are isomeric and similar to phenelfamycin E and F only with the addition of a hydroxyl group at position C-30. Phenelfamycin G and H have a narrow antibacterial spectrum with potent activity against Propionibacterium acnes.

Name: ganefromycin
Description: One of a small group of kirromycin-like elfamycins which lack the pyridone moiety. Ganefromycin is produced by Streptomyces lydicus spp. tanzanius, and was considered for use as a growth promoting antibiotic in agriculture.

Name: mdtK
Description: A multidrug and toxic compound extrusions (MATE) transporter conferring resistance to norfloxacin, doxorubicin and acriflavine.

Name: mdfA
Description: Multidrug translocase MdfA

Name: mdtG
Description: Efflux protien mdtG.

Name: mdtD
Description: Efflux pump mdtD

Name: MexVW-OprM
Description: MexVW-OprM is a multidrug efflux protein expressed in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexV is the membrane fusion protein; MexW is the RND-type membrane protein; and OprM is the outer membrane channel. MexVW-OprM is associated with resistance to fluoroquinolones, tetracycline, chloramphenicol, erythromycin and acriflavine.

Name: mexV
Description: MexV is the membrane fusion protein of the MexVW-OprM multidrug efflux complex.

Name: mexW
Description: MexW is the RND-type membrane protein of the efflux complex MexVW-OprM.

Name: MexXY-OprM
Description: MexXY-OprM is a multidrug efflux protein expressed in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. MexY is the membrane fusion protein; MexX is the RND-type membrane protein; and OprM is the outer membrane channel. MexXY-OprM is associated with resistance to acriflavine, erythromycin, norfloxacin	 and ofloxacin.

Name: mexY
Description: MexY is the RND-type membrane protein of the efflux complex MexXY-OprM.

Name: mexX

Name: oleB

Name: opcM
Description: OpcM is an outer membrane factor protein found in Burkholderia cepacia. It is part of the CeoAB-OpcM complex.

Name: MexXY-OprA

Name: oprA
Description: OprA is an outer membrane factor protein found in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. It is part of the MexXY-OprA complex.

Name: beta-lactam resistant penicillin-binding proteins

Name: viomycin phosphotransferase

Name: ykkD

Name: lipopeptide antibiotic resistance gene

Name: Staphylococcus aureus cls conferring resistance to daptomycin
Description: cls or cardiolipin synthetase is an inner membrane protein that is involved in membrane synthesis. Specific mutations in S. aureus can confer resistance to daptomycin.

Name: daptomycin resistant liaFSR
Description: liaFSR is a two-component signal transduction pathway in B. subtilis that responds to peptide and lipopeptide antibiotics. The liaFSR two-component system consists of a histidine kinase liaS and the response regulator liaR as well as the accessory protein liaF, which acts as a negative regulator of liaRS-dependent signal transduction. Mutations confer resistance to daptomycin.

Name: Enterococcus faecalis liaF mutant conferring daptomycin resistance
Description: liaF is an accessory protein that acts as a negative regulator of liaRS signal transduction pathway. Mutations confer daptomycin resistance.

Name: Enterococcus faecium liaR mutant conferring daptomycin resistance
Description: liaR is a response regulator found in the liaFSR signal transduction pathway. Mutations confer daptomycin resistance.

Name: Enterococcus faecium liaS mutant conferring daptomycin resistance
Description: liaS is a histidine kinase found in the liaFSR signal transduction pathway. Mutations confer daptomycin resistance.

Name: daptomycin resistant pgsA
Description: pgsA or phosphatidylglycerophosphate synthetase is an integral membrane protein involved in phospholipid biosynthesis. It is a CDP-diacylglycerol-glycerol-3-phosphate 3-phosphatidyltransferase. Laboratory experiments have detected mutations conferring daptomycin resistance in Entercoccus.

Name: daptomycin resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB)
Description: Daptomycin resistant RNA polymerases include amino acids substitutions which alter expression of the dlt operon, which increases the cell surface positive charge. Known from S. aureus.

Name: daptomycin resistant mprF
Description: MprF is a integral membrane protein that modifies the negatively-charged phosphatidylglycerol on the membrane surface of both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. This confers resistance to cationic peptides that disrupt the cell membrane, including defensins. Mutations in mprF can additionally confer resistance to daptomycin in S. aureus.

Name: Enterococcus faecium cls conferring resistance to daptomycin
Description: cls or cardiolipin synthetase is an inner membrane protein that is involved in membrane synthesis. Specific mutations in Enterococcus can confer resistance to daptomycin.

Name: GIM beta-lactamase
Description: The GIM beta-lactamases are isolated from Pseudomonas aeruginosa. They are located in a distinct integron structure. They confers high broad spectrum resistant, including all ß-lactams, aminoglycosides and quinolones.

Name: tet45
Description: tet45 is a tetracycline efflux pump found in Bhargavaea cecembensis strain previously isolated from a poultry-litter-impacted soil.

Name: aadA25
Description: streptomycin/spectinomycin resistance gene found in Pasteurella multocida isolated from bovine respiratory tract

Name: rmtH
Description: rmtH is a 16s ribosomal RNA methyltransferase found in Klebsiella pneumoniae strain MRSN2404 that was isolated from the chronic wound of a soldier wounded in Iraq in 2006. It confers high resistance to all aminoglycosides

Name: AAC(6')-Iak
Description: AAC(6')-Iak is a 6'-N-aminoglycoside acetyltransferase-encoding gene isolated from a multidrug-resistant clinical isolate of Stenotrophomonas maltophilia

Name: AAC(6')-Ian
Description: AAC(6')-Ian is an amikacin acetyltransferase gene found on a transferable plasmid of the Serratia marcescens strain NUBL-11663. IT catalyze the transfer of an acetyl group from acetyl coenzyme A onto an amine at the 6'-position of various aminoglycosides.

Name: TLA beta-lactamase
Description: The TLA beta-lactamases are resistant to expanded-spectrum cephalosporins, aztreonam, ciprofloxacin, and ofloxacin but was susceptible to amikacin, cefotetan, and imipenem.

Name: TLA-1
Description: TLA-1 is a beta-lactamase found in plasmids of clinical isolates of Escherichia coli strain R170 in Latin America. It preferentially hydrolyzed cephaloridine, cefotaxime, cephalothin, benzylpenicillin, and ceftazidime. The enzyme was markedly inhibited by sulbactam, tazobactam, and clavulanic acid.

Name: TLA-2
Description: TLA-2 is a beta-lactamase is present on a plasmid isolated from an unidentified bacterial strain from a waste water treatment plant. The enzyme mostly hydrolyzes cephalosporins.

Name: TLA-3
Description: TLA-3 is a beta-lactamase found in a transferable plasmid of Serratia marcescens clinical isolate. It confers resistance to ceftazidime, cefotaxime and cefepime, but not to cefmetazole and meropenem

Name: Erm(43)
Description: Erm(43) is a macrolide, lincosamide, and streptogramin B resistance gene found in Staphylococcus lentus chromosome isolated from human, dog and chicken.

Name: lsaE
Description: lsaE is a ABC transporter gene found in porcine MRSA isolates. It confers resistance to pleuromutilin, lincosamide, and streptogramin A

Name: FosK
Description: FosK is a fosfomycin thiol transferase isolated from Acinetobacter soli. It is integrin-mediated. It confers a high level of resistance to fosfomycin.

Name: FosXCC

Name: 16S rRNA with mutation conferring antibiotic resistance
Description: Many antibiotics inhibit the growth of bacteria by blocking protein synthesis on the ribosome. The antibiotic-binding sites are located within functionally important structures in the ribosomal RNA. Antibiotic resistance is often conferred by base substitutions or methylations at these sites in the rRNA. Point mutations in the bacterial 16S ribosomal RNA in the small 30S subunit can confer resistance to antibiotics.

Description: Aminoglycosides bind to the 16S rRNA, at the tRNA acceptor A-site (aminoacyl site) and inhibit protein translation process. Mutations in the nucleotide sequence in this area can result in resistance to aminoglycoside antibiotics.

Name: cell membrane component enzymes targeted by antibiotic

This confers resistance to cationic peptides that disrupt the cell membrane, including defensins. Mutations in this enzyme can confer additional resistances.

Name: Salmonella enterica ramR mutants

Name: Klebsiella pneumoniae ramR mutants
Description: RamR is a repressor that regulates RamA expression. Mutations lead to the upregulation of AcrAB, which is positively regulated by RamA.

Name: Escherichia coli soxR mutants
Description: SoxR is a sensory protein that upregulates soxS expression in the presence of redox-cycling drugs. This stress response leads to the expression many multidrug efflux pumps.

Name: Salmonella serovars soxS mutants

Name: Mycobacterium leprae dapsone resistant folP mutants

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis katG mutations conferring resistance to isoniazid

Mutations in katG results in inability to activate isoniazid. Over 280 different mutations have been documented in PubMed for katG, with mutations to Ser315 being the most prevalent.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis inhA mutations conferring resistance to isoniazid
Description: inhA is a enoyl-acyl carrier reductase used in lipid metabolism and farry acid biosynthesis. It is inhibited by isoniazid. mutations in the promoter region or multiple copies of the inhA shows marked resistance to isoniazid mediated inhibition of mycolic acid biosynthesis.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis pncA mutations conferring resistance to pyrazinamide
Description: pncA is a pyrazinamidase/nicotinamidase. It catalyzes the activation of pyrazinamide. Some mutation within pncA are associated with loss of enzyme activity, resulting in pyrazinamide resistance.

Description:
Ribosomal protein S12 stabilizes the highly conserved
pseudoknot structure formed by 16S rRNA. Amino acid
substitutions in RpsL affect the higher-order structure of 16S
rRNA and confer streptomycin resistance by disrupting interactions between 16S rRNA and streptomycin.

Name: pyrazinamide
Description: Pyrazinamide is an Antimycobacterial. It is highly specific and active only against Mycobacterium tuberculosis. This compound is a prodrug and needs to be activated inside the cell. It interferes with the bacterium's ability to synthesize new fatty acids, causing cell death.

Name: LFF571
Description: LFF571 is a novel semi-synthetic thiopeptide antibiotic derived from GE2270. It has been shown to possess potent in vitro and in vivo activity against Gram-positive bacteria. It is hypothesized that it a translation inhibitor leading to cell death.

Name: antibiotic resistant katG

Mutations that arises within this protein cause changes that results in the inability for katG to activate antibiotics, conferring resistance

Name: antibiotic resistant inhA
Description: inhA is a enoyl-acyl carrier reductase used in lipid metabolism and farry acid biosynthesis. It is inhibited by isoniazid. mutations in the promoter region or multiple copies of the inhA shows marked resistance to isoniazid mediated inhibition of mycolic acid biosynthesis.

Name: antibiotic resistant pncA

Name: antibiotic resistant mprF

LPG synthesis contributes to bacterial virulence as it is involved in the resistance mechanism against cationic antimicrobial peptides (CAMP) produces by the host's immune system (defensins, cathelicidins) and by the competing microorganisms (bacteriocins)

Name: antibiotic resistant arabinosyltransferase

Name: antibiotic resistant dfr

Description: RNA polymerase is a multisubunit enzyme that is necessary for transcription. The beta-prime subunit of RNA polymerase forms the active center of the enzyme and template/transcript binding sites. This enzyme can be inactivated by antibiotics leading to cell death.

Name: fluoroquinolone sensitive parE
Description: ParE is a subunit of topoisomerase IV, necessary for cell survival. Point mutations in ParE prevent fluoroquinolones from inhibiting DNA synthesis, thus conferring resistance.

Name: antibiotic sensitive Ribosomal protein S12 (rpsL)
Description: Ribosomal protein S12 stabilizes the highly conserved pseudoknot structure formed by 16S rRNA. It is targeted and inhibited by streptomycin

Name: isoniazid resistance gene
Description: Genetic determinants which confer resistance to isoniazid.

Name: pyrazinamide resistance gene
Description: Genetic determinants conferring resistance to lipopeptide antibiotics.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis 16S rRNA mutation conferring resistance to aminoglycosides
Description: Aminoglycosides bind to the 16S rRNA, at the tRNA acceptor A-site (aminoacyl site) and inhibit protein translation process. Mutations in the nucleotide sequence in this area can result in resistance to aminoglycosides.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis 16S rRNA mutation conferring resistance to kanamycin
Description: Point mutations in the 3' domain of 16S rRNA of Mycobacterium tuberculosis can confer resistance to kanamycin.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis 16S rRNA mutation conferring resistance to viomycin
Description: Peptide antibiotics inhibit protein synthesis. Resistance to viomycin can be caused by an altered RNA molecule in the 16S ribosomal subunit.

Name: Enterococcus faecium EF-Tu mutants conferring resistance to GE2270A
Description: Sequence variants of Enterococcus faecium elongation factor Tu that confer resistance to GE2270A

Name: antibiotic sensitive RNA polymerase switch region
Description: The switch region is a structural element that mediates conformational changes and contacts required for RNAP to load DNA into the RNAP active-center cleft during transcription initiation. The switch region is located at the base of the RNAP "clamp" and serves as the "hinge" that mediates opening of the RNAP clamp to load DNA into the RNAP active-center cleft and mediates closing of the RNAP clamp to retain DNA in the RNAP active-center cleft.

Name: mecB
Description: A foreign PBP2 acquired by lateral gene transfer that able to perform peptidoglycan synthesis in the presence of beta-lactams.

Name: cfrA
Description: Cfr enzyme adds an additional methyl group at position 8 of A2503 in 23S rRNA, resulting in resistance to florfenicol.

Name: DrrAB
Description: DrrAB is dedicated ATP binding cassette type transporter for the export of doxorubicin and daunorubicin in Streptomyces peucetius. Further studies with  H33342 and EtBr suggest that it is a multidrug transporter.

Name: Antibiotic resistant tlyA
Description: tlyA encodes for hemolysin. It Catalyzes the 2'-O-methylation at nucleotides C1409 in 16S rRNA and C1920 in 23S rRNA. Mutation that arise within this gene reduces the binding affinity of aminoglycosides to rRNA

Name: Aminoglycosides resistant tlyA
Description: mutations within the tlyA protein that causes resistance to aminoglycosides

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis tlyA mutations conferring resistance to aminoglycosides
Description: Specific mutations that arise in Mycobacterium tuberculosis tlyA resulting in aminoglycosides resistance

Name: Antibiotic resistant iniA
Description: iniA, an isoniazid-induced protein, is part of the iniBAC operon that participates in the development of tolerance to both isoniazid and ethambutol. May function through a MDR-pump like mechanism, although it does not appear to directly transport isoniazid from the cell

Name: Ethambutol resistant iniA
Description: Mutations that occurs on the iniA genes resulting in the resistance to ethambutol

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis iniA mutant conferring resistance to Ethambutol
Description: Specific mutations in Mycobacterium tuberculosis iniA resulting in resistance to ethambutol

Name: Antibiotic resistant iniC

Name: Ethambutol resistant iniC
Description: Mutations that occurs on the iniC genes resulting in the resistance to ethambutol

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis iniC mutant conferring resistance to ethambutol
Description: Specific mutations that occurs on Mycobacterium tuberculosis iniC causing it to be ethambutol resistant.

Name: ethambutol resistant embA

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis embR mutant conferring resistance to ethambutol

Name: antibiotic resistant ethA
Description: Monooxygenase able to convert a wide range of ketones to the corresponding esters or lactones via a Baeyer-Villiger oxidation reaction. It is responsible for the activation of several thiocarbamide-containing pro-drugs into cytotoxic species

Name: ethionamide resistant ethA
Description: Mutations that occurs on the ethA genes resulting in the inability to catalyzes the oxidation of ethionamide (ETH) to the corresponding sulfoxide (the active drug)

Name: mycobacterium tuberculosis ethA mutant conferring resistance to ethionamide
Description: Specific mutations that occurs on Mycobacterium tuberculosis ethA causing it to be ethionamide resistant

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis gyrB mutant conferring resistance to fluoroquinolone
Description: Point mutation in Mycobacterium tuberculosis gyrB resulting in fluoroquinolone resistance

Name: antibiotic resistant ndh
Description: ndh is a NADH oxidase. It participates in antibiotic resistance by diminishing NADH oxidation and consequently causes an increase in NADH concentration and depletion of NAD+. This alteration of the NADH/NAD+ ratio prevents the peroxidation reactions required for the activation of INH, as well as the displacement of the NADH-isonicotinic acyl complex from InhA enzyme binding site.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis ndh mutant conferring resistance to isoniazid
Description: Mutations in the Mycobacterium tuberculosis ndh gene that results in increased resistance to isoniazid.

Name: antibiotic resistant kasA
Description: kasA is a  ketoacyl acyl carrier protein synthase that catalyzes the condensation reaction of fatty acid synthesis by the addition to an acyl acceptor of two carbons from malonyl-ACP. It is involved in elongation of fatty acids intermediate in the biosynthetic pathway of mycolic acids.

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis kasA mutant conferring resistance to isoniazid
Description: Specific mutations on the Mycobacterium tuberculosis kasA gene resulting in lowered affinity of isoniazid, resulting in resistance

Name: rifamycin resistant arabinosyltransferase

Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis embB mutants conferring resistance to rifampicin

Name: antibiotic resistant gidB

Name: PmrE
